<DOC><DOCNO> AP890918-0142 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-09-18-89 1844EDT</FILEID><FIRST>u a AM-WeatherpageWeather     09-18 0342</FIRST><SECOND>AM-Weatherpage Weather,0350</SECOND><HEAD>Hurricane Hugo Hits Puerto Rico</HEAD><BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE><TEXT>   Hurricane Hugo brushed across Puerto Rico on Monday, bringingsustained winds near 125 mph and heavy rain, causing extensivedamage and interfering with communications.   Hugo, the most powerful storm to strike the region in a decade,was blamed for at least 14 deaths.   Meteorologist Jesse Moore at the National Hurricane Center saidit was too early to tell if Hugo would strike the U.S. mainland. Hesaid it was expected to be off the southeastern Bahamas by Wednesdayand ``after that, it's anybody's guess.''   Behind Hugo, Tropical Storm Iris was about 300 miles from theLesser Antilles with a maximum sustained wind speed of around 50mph. Strengthening was not expected because of the proximity of Hugo.   Elsewhere, showers and thunderstorms were widespread across muchof the Florida Peninsula, south of a frontal system in very warmhumid air. Hail the size of golf balls pelted Amelia Island duringthe morning, the National Weather Service said. A tornado wasreported at Fernandina Beach near Amelia Island, the weather servicesaid.   Showers and thunderstorms were scattered over the central PacificCoast and into the northern Rockies as low pressure in the upperatmosphere developed over Northern California. Street flooding wasreported in parts of Sacramento, Calif., the weather service said.   Temperatures around the nation at 3 p.m. EDT ranged from 38degrees at Truckee, Calif., to 94 at Brownsville, Texas. Monday'slow in the Lower 48 states was 30 at both Burns and Redmond, Ore.   For Tuesday, widespread showers and isolated thunderstorms wereforecast from central and Southern California into Wyoming andcentral South Dakota. Scattered showers and thunderstorms wereforecast from Florida across the southern and middle Atlantic Coast.   Highs only in the 60s were predicted across the PacificNorthwest, the Great Basin of Nevada and western Utah, and thenorthern parts of New England; in the low to mid 90s across much ofTexas; and in the 70s or 80s across much of the rest of the nation.</TEXT></DOC>